I have such a problem for a while and best solution i found is this:

Add a static Class to Your Library Modules:

    export class Lib1Module {
      static forRoot(config: any): ModuleWithProviders {
        return {
          ngModule: Lib1Module,
          providers: [{provide: &#39;config&#39;, useValue: config}]
        };
      }
    }

    export class Lib2Module {
      static forRoot(config: any): ModuleWithProviders {
        return {
          ngModule: Lib2Module,
          providers: [{provide: &#39;config&#39;, useValue: config}]
        };
      }
    }

Then pass `environment` from `app.module` to your `Lib1Module` &amp; `Lib2Module` Like this:

    imports:[
        CommonModule,
        BrowserAnimationsModule,
        ReactiveFormsModule,
        HttpClientModule,
        RouterModule,
        BrowserModule,
        FormsModule,
        GigLib1Module.forRoot(environment),
        GigLib2Module.forRoot(environment)
    ]

Now, `environment` file injected into your library.

How to use it:

    environment :any
    constructor(@Inject(&#39;config&#39;) config) 
    {         
         if (config) {
         this.environment = config;
       } 
    }

Now Environment can be changed from Main Project easily.

